# myClawTeam Blog Architecture Plan

## Product anchor

Build the myClawTeam Blog: a dark, modern, red-accented SSR blog with the homepage headline "myClawTeam Blog" and slogan "By talking, serious delivery." Public pages show published posts, category filters, RSS, sitemap, metadata, and newsletter signup. Admin pages provide signed-cookie authentication, media uploads to Object Storage, post CRUD, publishing controls, and subscriber viewing.

## Stack and build shape

- Rust edition 2024 cargo-leptos workspace using latest compatible Leptos 0.x full-stack SSR and Axum integration.
- Server-side rendering with a hydrating client bundle; use `cargo leptos build` for release builds.
- Tailwind CSS for styling, with shared design tokens for dark surfaces, red accent, typography, focus rings, forms, cards, and loading/error states.
- PostgreSQL via sqlx with checked queries where practical, migrations under `migrations/`, and a shared `PgPool` provided through Axum/Leptos context.
- S3-compatible Object Storage client configured from env, wrapped behind a small storage service API so upload handlers and tests do not depend on provider details.

## Proposed module structure

- `Cargo.toml`, `Cargo.leptos.toml`: workspace/build configuration.
- `src/main.rs`: Axum server entrypoint, config load, pool/storage/session setup, Leptos route mounting, static assets, feed/sitemap/robots routes.
- `src/lib.rs`: Leptos app entrypoint and hydration target.
- `src/app.rs`: router, root layout, route groups, error boundary wiring.
- `src/config.rs`: typed env config for database, admin credentials, session secret, public site URL, Object Storage, upload limits.
- `src/state.rs`: application state shared with Axum handlers and Leptos server functions.
- `src/auth.rs`: credential validation, signed session cookie issue/verify/clear, auth extractor/helpers.
- `src/middleware.rs`: `/admin` guard and redirect/logout behavior.
- `src/db/mod.rs`: pool creation, migration runner, repository namespace.
- `src/db/posts.rs`, `src/db/media.rs`, `src/db/subscribers.rs`, `src/db/categories.rs`: sqlx repository/query utilities.
- `src/models.rs`: shared structs/enums for posts, categories, media, subscribers, pagination, publish status, and form payloads.
- `src/routes/public/*`: homepage, post listing, category listing, post detail, newsletter server function, metadata helpers.
- `src/routes/admin/*`: login, dashboard, post list, create/edit form, media picker, subscribers page.
- `src/components/public/*`: header, footer, post card, category nav, newsletter form, rich content renderer.
- `src/components/admin/*`: admin shell, tables, forms, media upload/picker, confirmation controls.
- `src/storage.rs`: Object Storage client and `put_object`/URL helpers.
- `src/upload.rs`: multipart handler, MIME/extension/size validation, metadata persistence.
- `src/feeds.rs`: RSS/Atom, sitemap, and robots response builders.
- `tests/`: focused integration/unit coverage for auth/session, repositories, upload validation, and the full admin-to-public flow.

## Data model

- `categories`: `id`, `slug` unique, `name` unique, `sort_order`, timestamps. Seed `thoughts`, `product-progress`, `announcements`.
- `posts`: `id`, `title`, `slug` unique, `body` rich content string, `category_id`, `status` draft/published, `published_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`; indexes on status/date, category/status/date, slug.
- `media`: `id`, `object_key` unique, `url`, `media_type` image/video, `content_type`, `size_bytes`, `created_at`.
- `newsletter_subscribers`: `id`, `email` unique, `created_at`.

Keep rich post body storage simple initially: sanitized HTML or markdown-compatible content with explicit media embed tokens/HTML generated by the admin UI. Store media metadata separately and embed URLs in content for rendering.

## Issue dependency plan

1. Foundation: #1 creates the Leptos/Axum SSR project; #2 Tailwind theme; #3 sqlx/Postgres; #4 typed env; #5 storage client; #6 app shell/routing.
2. Database layer: #7 posts/categories schema; #8 media schema; #9 subscribers schema; #10 category seed; #11 repository utilities.
3. Auth/admin access: #12 session cookie and credential validation; #13 login server function/page; #14 admin middleware and logout.
4. Media pipeline: #15 streaming upload to Object Storage and media table; #16 content-type/size validation; #17 admin media picker.
5. Post management: #18 post CRUD server functions; #19 admin post dashboard; #20 create/edit form with media embedding; #21 publish/delete controls.
6. Public experience: #22 shared UI components; #23 homepage; #24 pagination; #25 category filters; #26 detail page; #27 newsletter signup; #28 admin subscribers.
7. Publishing polish: #29 metadata/OG; #30 sitemap and robots; #31 RSS.
8. Quality/deploy: #32 unit tests; #33 loading/error review; #34 end-to-end test; #35 self-hosted build/run documentation.

## Key design decisions

- Use server functions for form-oriented app actions and plain Axum handlers for multipart upload, feeds, sitemap, robots, and middleware-sensitive routes.
- Centralize all env reads in `Config`; no route/component should read env directly.
- Keep auth intentionally simple: one admin credential pair from env plus a signed, HTTP-only, SameSite session cookie with a secret from env.
- Treat Object Storage as write-once public media for this scope; store object key and public URL in Postgres so public pages do not need storage API calls.
- Prefer repository functions as the boundary between server functions and sqlx, making tests direct and keeping database behavior consistent.
- Use stable slugs and pagination contracts early so sitemap, RSS, category pages, and detail pages all share the same published-post queries.
- Keep admin and public components separated while sharing only neutral primitives and shared models.
- Build test seams around auth signing, upload validation, and repositories before the end-to-end flow so later issues can add coverage incrementally.
